    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[What is the area \(A\) of an isosceles triangle with two equal sides of length \(x\) and apex angle \(\theta\)? Express your answer as a function of \(x\) and \(\sin \theta\).
<br><p>
\(A=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]</p><p>Hint: Use the following diagram</p><p><img src="@@PLUGINFILE@@/4.3%20fig%201%20isosceles%20triangle.svg" alt="Isosceles triangle with apex angle theta and bisector at apex" role="presentation" class="img-responsive atto_image_button_text-bottom" width="196" height="172">]]></text>
<file name="4.3 fig 1 isosceles triangle.svg" path="/" encoding="base64"></file>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[The right-angled triangle \(ACD\) has area \(\dfrac{1}{2} (CD)(AD)\)
\(\begin{eqnarray*}\text{But}\qquad \sin \left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)=\dfrac{CD}{x}\qquad
 &amp;\therefore&amp;\quad CD=x\sin \left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)\\
\\
\cos\left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)=\dfrac{AD}{x}\qquad &amp;\therefore&amp;\quad AD=x\cos\left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)\end{eqnarray*}\)
\(\begin{eqnarray*}\therefore\qquad \text{area of}\ \ \ \Delta ACD&amp;=&amp;
\dfrac{1}{2}x^2\sin\left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)\cos\left(\dfrac{\theta}{2}\right)=\dfrac{1}{4} x^2\sin \theta\\
\\
\\
\therefore\qquad \text{area of}\ \ \ \Delta ABC&amp;=&amp; 2\times \text{area of}\ \Delta ACD
=\dfrac{1}{2} x^2\sin \theta\end{eqnarray*}\)]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
